ers in Ohio, Korie Litte Edwards and Michelle Oyakawa uncover several reasons, including a move away from engagement with independent Black-led civic groups toward white-controlled faith-based organizations, religious leaders’ nostalgia for and personal links to the legacy of the civil rights movement, the challenges of organizing around race-based oppression in an allegedly post-racial world, and the hierarchical structure of the Black religious leadership network, which may impede ministers’ work towards collective activism. Black clergy continue to care deeply about social justice and racial oppression. This book offers important insights into how they approach these issues today, illuminating the social processes that impact when, how, and why they participate in civic action in twenty-first-century America. It reveals the structure and limitations of the Black religious-leader community and its capacity for broad-based mobilization in the post–civil rights era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American clergyxPolitical activity. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxElectiony21st century. 7aRELIGION / Leadership.2bisacsh  aAfrican American church.  aAfrican American churches.  aAfrican American.  aBarack Obama.  aBlack church.  aBlack pastor.  aBlack religious leader.  aBlack religious leaders.  aCharismatic leader.  aCivic Organizing.  aCivic organizations.  aCivil Rights Movement.  aCommunity organizing.  aCulture.  aEvangelicals.  aFBCO.  aFaith Based Community Organizing.  aFrames.  aLeadership.  aMobilization.  aPastor.  aProtestant ethic.  aRace.  aRacial attitudes.  aRacial identity.  aRacial inequality.  aReligious leader.  aReligious leaders.  aRepublicans.  aSocial Movements.